In article <2t29fe$f81@sundog.tiac.net> huricane@max.tiac.net (Pierce Nichols) writes:
>Alan Anderson (anderson@kosepc01.delcoelect.com) wrote:
>: In <60.3800.4262.0N1A0B28@canrem.com>, 
>: sander.schimmelpenninck@canrem.com (Sander Schimmelpenninck) quotes:
>: > [...]
>: >      ``People who want to work around Clipper will be able to
>: >do it,'' said Martin Hellman, a Stanford University cryptologist,
>: >who has read a paper circulated by Blaze.
>
>: More like "People who want to work around Law Enforcement Access will be
>: able to do it while still working within Clipper."
>
>	It's easy - just build a hardware box that strips the LEAF. Not a 
>big problem.

<sigh>  Hardly... each clipper chip must receive a valid (or
what it *thinks* is valid) LEAF to operate.  If you strip the
LEAF(s), the chips will refuse to communicate.  So far the best
way around this seems to be Matt Blaze's hack to create LEAF's
that the chips *think* are valid, even though the do not contain
the correct session key.

